com.github.dakusui.scriptiveunit.runners

Enum RunningMode

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<RunningMode>
      • com.github.dakusui.scriptiveunit.runners.RunningMode
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Comparable<RunningMode>

    public enum RunningMode
extends Enum<RunningMode>

    An Enum that provides definitions of the ScriptiviUnit's execution modes.

    Here are definitions that are used in explanations of those execution modes.

    Test Case, Test Fixture, and Common Fixture

    In Scriptive Unit, A test suite consists of test cases and by executing all test all oracles for each test cases, the entire suite will be executed.

    One test case is a tuple, which is a Map whose key is a String. We can think of a test suite where some keys of all the test cases have the constant values for all the test cases in the suite.

    Such entries are called a common fixture and they can be accessed from suite level actions, which are setUpBeforeAll and tearDownAfterAll.

    A test fixture is implicitly defined by a user. In setUp and tearDown actions, a user may access some values of a test case. The keys that the user used to access them will be a part of a test fixture.

    Following is a diagram that illustrates the relationships between test cases, test fixtures, and the common fixture.

    fixtureOf(TestCase testCase)

    A function that returns a test fixture from a given test case by projecting only a related portion of it.

    exercise(TestOracle testOracle, TestCase testCase)

    A function that exercise a given test oracle with a given test case. Following pseudo code snippet illustrates a control flow of it.

    Note that this snippet is only for illustration and ScriptiveUnit constructs a tree of actions that models this flow first and execute it.

    void exercise(TestOracle testOracle, TestCase testCase) {
  testOracle.before(testCase);
  try {
      if (testOracle.given(testCase))
        testOracle.then(testCase, testOracle.when(testCase));
      else
        throw new TestIgnored();
  } catch (Failure f) {
      throw testOracle.handleFailure(f, testCase);
  } finally {
    testOracle.after(testCase);
  }
}
    setUp and tearDown

    setUp and tearDown are actions created from a test fixture.

        public static final RunningMode GROUP_BY_TEST_ORACLE

        A mode where test executions are grouped by test oracles first.

        structure
        sequence
        setUpBeforeAll(commonFixture)
try {
  for (TestOracle eachTestOracle: allTestOracles) {
    for (TestCase eachTestCase: allTestCases) {
      setUp(fixtureOf(eachTestCase));
      try {
        exercise(eachTestOracle, eachTestCase);
      } finally {
        tearDown(fixtureOf(eachTestCase));
      }
    }
  }
} finally {
  tearDownAfterAll(commonFixture)
}

      }

  }

      • GROUP_BY_TEST_FIXTURE

        public static final RunningMode GROUP_BY_TEST_FIXTURE

        A mode where test executions are grouped by test fixtures first.

        In case you know that your oracles do not modify your SUT (i.e. they are repeatable) and it is expensive and necessary to build your SUT based on test fixtures, using this mode would make a sense.

        In this mode, setUp and tearDown are performed only once for each test fixture. For each test case that belongs to the test fixture, all oracles are exercised.

        structure
        sequence
        setUpBeforeAll(commonFixture)
try {
  for (TestFixture eachTestFixture: allTestFixtures) {
    setUp(eachTestFixture);
    try {
      for (TestCase eachTestCase: testCasesFor(eachTestFixture)) {
        for (TestOracle eachTestOracle: allTestOracles) {
          exercise(eachTestOracle, eachTestCase);
        }
      }
    } finally {
      tearDown(eachTestFixture);
    }
  }
} finally {
  tearDownAfterAll(commonFixture)
}

        Note that this snippet is only for illustration and ScriptiveUnit constructs a tree of actions that models this flow first and execute it.

      • GROUP_BY_TEST_FIXTURE_ORDER_BY_TEST_ORACLE

        public static final RunningMode GROUP_BY_TEST_FIXTURE_ORDER_BY_TEST_ORACLE

        A mode where test executions are grouped by test fixtures first and then ordered by test oracles.

        This is similar to Type.GROUP_BY_TEST_FIXTURE, but concrete test oracles are ordered by test oracle definitions first and then by test cases within a fixture.

        That is, main actions are constructed in a manner illustrated in the following diagram.

        sequence
        setUpBeforeAll(commonFixture)
try {
  for (TestFixture eachTestFixture: allTestFixtures) {
    setUp(eachTestFixture);
    try {
      for (TestOracle eachTestOracle: allTestOracles) {
        for (TestCase eachTestCase: testCasesFor(eachTestFixture)) {
          exercise(eachTestOracle, eachTestCase);
        }
      }
    } finally {
      tearDown(eachTestFixture);
    }
  }
} finally {
  tearDownAfterAll(commonFixture)
}

        Note that this snippet is only for illustration and ScriptiveUnit constructs a tree of actions that models this flow first and execute it.
